(noun) An abstract unit of area measurement used mostly in the British isles (Britain, Scotland, Ireland, etc.) and largely disregarded after the fifteenth century. Although defined as a unit relative to the amount of land that a gang of oxen are assigned to plow during a single year, it was generally agreed to be approximately 14 square miles. After the widespread use of crop rotation, however, the oxgang became too difficult a unit to apply, thus explaining its fall from common usage.